uctive theory based on analysis of how the global power structure and domestic politics affect alliances. As China becomes stronger and the U.S. military budget shrinks, The Supply Side of Security shows that these countries should be understood not just as competing threats, but as competing security suppliers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aAlliancesvCase studies. 0aAlliancesxCase studies. 0aInternational relations. 4aChina. 4aEast Asia. 4aJapan. 4aSouth Korea. 4aSpain. 4aUS foreign policy. 4aalliances. 4adomestic politics. 4ainternational bargaining. 4apolarity. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804798594zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804798594423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804798594.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles